    "summary": "Yes TN, but frame as connection not warning — resonance is intentional",
    "content": "\n**Yes to a TN, but frame it as a connection, not a warning.**\n\nA philosophically literate English reader who encounters \"category theory\" in a philosophical text about cognitive structure WILL think of Kant. That is not confusion -- it is a correct instinct, since the author's S_E (stable structures as conditions of possibility for experience) is explicitly Kantian in spirit. A \"not to be confused with\" note would sever a connection the author wants to preserve.\n\nBetter framing for the TN: \"Category theory (范畴论) here refers to the mathematical discipline (objects, morphisms, functors), not directly to Kant's categories (Kategorien) of the understanding. However, the resonance is not accidental: the author's stable structures S_E play a role analogous to Kantian categories as conditions for the possibility of experience. See [K1策略, section on stable structures].\"\n\nThis does three things: (1) disambiguates for the reader who genuinely does not know mathematical category theory, (2) validates the Kantian association for the reader who does see it, (3) points forward to where the connection becomes explicit. It orients without patronizing.\n"
  }
